  "prompt": "Why sound waves cannot be polarized?",
  "response": "Sound waves cannot be polarized because they are longitudinal waves, meaning that the oscillations of the particles in the medium occur in the same direction as the wave's propagation. \n\nPolarization is a property of transverse waves, where the oscillations are perpendicular to the direction of the wave's propagation. In transverse waves, such as electromagnetic waves, the oscillations can occur in different planes, allowing for different polarizations (e.g., horizontal, vertical, or circular).\n\nIn the case of sound waves, since the oscillations are along the direction of propagation, there is no possibility for different orientations of the oscillations. Therefore, sound waves cannot be polarized.",
